         <entryFree xml:id="feature_name_here" type="architectural-feature">
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="en" type="preferred" source="#biblk000029-1">superficial bracket-arms (preferred)</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">扶壁栱</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">扶壁栱</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-6" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin" source="#biblk000029-3">fúbìgǒng</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-5" xml:lang="Wade-Giles">fu-pi-kung</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation" source="#biblk000029-2">wall supporting bracket-arm (lit.)</term>
         	
            <note type="Note (brief)">
               <p xml:lang="en">In the <title>Yingzao fashi</title> (1103) this term refers to square beams carved with bracket-arms in low relief and layered within the wall plane above pillar tops. It can also refer to the entire composition of square beams and bracket-arms within the wall plane above pillar tops (Cheng Mingda 2010; Xu Yitao 2005). Also called “shadow bracket-arm(s)” (<term ref="https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000118">yinggong 影栱</term>).</p>
         		<p xml:lang="zh-Hant">見於北宋官書<title>《營造法式》</title>（1103），指柱頭一綫之上所用之方刻出栱的形象。又名影栱。又一説認爲指柱頭一綫鋪作組合中的單栱、重栱、素方縂體（陳明達2010；徐怡濤 2005).</p>          
            </note>
            
            <note type="related concepts">
               <p><term ref="https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000118">影栱 yǐnggǒng</term></p>
            </note>
            
